The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 Metro Briefs

 A 35-year-old trader was seriously injured when he tried to prevent two youths from breaking into two jewellery shops in a Tara Chand Dutta Street highrise, in the Jorasanko police station area, at dawn on Wednesday. Raj Kumar Mishra, who lives on the third-floor of the house, saw the youths standing outside the shops around four in the morning. When he walked up to them and saw the locks of the shop doors broken, one of the youths pointed a revolver at him. As soon as Mishra screamed for help, the other youth hit him on the back of his head with a rod. The youths ran away with Mishras mobile and wallet. One of Mishras neighbours tried to stop them but failed. 

 Members of West Bengal United Minorities Forum organised a rally on Wednesday, demanding scrapping of West Bengal School Service Commission (Amendment) Bill, 2006. The government had assured the founding bodies of some Christian schools last year that it would not implement the bill. The forum submitted a memorandum to Governor Gopal Krishna Gandhi.

 A girl, studying in Class VII of an English-medium school in Entally, went missing on Wednesday. Her parents filed a missing diary with police, stating that she left her Chhatubabu Lane residence for school but did not turn up there. According to police, the girl may have eloped with her boyfriend.

 A Taltala police station truck lost control and rammed against the railing of an Indira Gandhi statue at the crossing of Taltala Avenue and SN Banerjee Road on Wednesday dawn. An assistant sub-inspector, a constable and the driver were seriously injured.

 Globsyn Business School on Wednesday announced a tie-up with Glasgow University for a postgraduate course in international business.

 Tarapada Mandal, 82, a resident of Shibpur, died after being run over by an unidentified vehicle near his home on Wednesday morning. 




